    <name>
      <text>5.2.5 (Find solutions of cosine equation exact negative)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find all of the solutions to the equation {@eqn@} in the range \(0 < x < 360^\circ\) Give your answers as a list, e.g. if you believe the solutions to be \(x= 10^\circ\) and \(x = 20^\circ\) enter <code>[x = 10,x = 20]</code></p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Since we have {@eqn@} we see that the value of \(\cos\) must be negative so we must have solutions in the second and third quadrants. In other words the solutions are of the form \(180^\circ + x\) and \(180^\circ - x\). We can obtain the angle corresponding to the first quadrant by using our calculator (or remembering) that 
\[
x = \cos^{-1} {@-1*ang@} 
\]
This gives us \(x = {@round(acosd(-ang))@}^\circ\). Hence to find the solutions of {@eqn@} we have
\[
180^\circ - {@round(acosd(-ang))@}^\circ  = {@soln1@}^\circ \qquad \mbox{ and } \qquad 180^\circ + {@round(acosd(-ang))@}^\circ  = {@soln2@}^\circ,
\]
Thus the solutions are
\[
{@ta1@},
\]
and these are the only solutions in the given range.</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
